==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swelt
<hw>Swelt</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>swelten</ets> to die, to
swoon or faint, AS. <ets>sweltan</ets> to die; akin to OD.
<ets>swelten</ets> to hunger, to fail, OS. <ets>sweltan</ets> to die,
Icel. <ets>svelta</ets> to die, to hunger, Sw. <ets>sv⟦aum⟧lta</ets> to
hunger, Dan. <ets>sulte</ets>, Goth. <ets>sviltan</ets> to die. Cf.
<er>Swelter</er>, <er>Sweltry</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To die; to
perish.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To faint; to swoon.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Night she <qex>swelt</qex> for passing joy.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swelt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swelt
<hw>Swelt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To overpower, as with heat; to
cause to faint; to swelter.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swelter</ent>⟦br⟧
